Reasoning: The paper deals with several well-known problems in Computational Geometry, such as $k$-center clustering and farthest nearest neighbor, which are typically studied in the cs.CG (Computational Geometry) sub-category. The paper also provides a general framework for getting expected linear time constant factor approximations to these problems, which involves designing efficient data structures and algorithms, and hence could be relevant to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses several problems involving distances and sets, which could be relevant to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of linear programming and optimization techniques, which could be relevant to the cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the extension of the framework to hold with high probability, which could be relevant to the cs.CC (Computational Complexity) sub-category.
